segments.text: From afar, she could already see how the sweet pea wrapped around the walls of the house, and unconsciously, she quickened her steps toward the entrance.
But even before she reached the door, she saw him standing in front of her as if he had been waiting for her arrival.
For a moment, she wondered why he hadn't opened the house with his key, which was always on the kitchen window sill.
After all, it was his house.
But then she noticed his embarrassed expression, and her stomach clenched at the thought that perhaps he no longer wanted her to come there.
Suddenly, as if afraid he might lose his courage, he started speaking quickly and without any introduction.
Look, I've thought about it, and it's clear to me that no one will do it better than you.
I see how clean and tidy it is here after every weekend you come.

It's certainly better than the piles of dust that accumulated in every corner during the months before you came, and definitely better than the garden that was almost wilting but is now starting to bloom again.
It keeps the house maintained, and I know it's good for you too.
I want just to arrange something so you can stay here at least until you finish your military service.
I have no plans for this house in the near future, and if that changes, I'll just let you know.
But there's the issue of the lease with the Aphrodare Company, which is part of the payment I made and costs me money every month.
I've already talked to Claude, and he's asking for you to meet with him to sort out just that part.
He poured everything out at once and fell silent.
She also remained silent, standing and looking at him in amazement, not knowing how to respond.
She felt panic spreading through her as if some danger was lurking.
He was imposing some responsibility on her that she wasn't sure she could handle.
After all, she was just hiding there knowing it was temporary, just for the meantime.
But it was precisely this arrangement where she slipped quietly into the room she chose and lived there for two days a week, sometimes only once every two weeks that suited her perfectly.
It allowed her a place to hide on the weekends to imagine it was still her home amidst the pictures of Josef and Lucy's recovering garden.
and sometimes to rent out a room or two and leave a few coins in the jar on the reception counter.
She had no idea how much was involved.
Could the rooms she rented out occasionally cover the lease?
Would she manage?
I don't know what to say.
Yehuda, are you sure this is what you want?
Came an excited horse voice from her throat.
Yes, look, he slowed down a bit.
The lease is not such a big deal.
And I'm not ashamed to say it also serves my interest in maintaining the property.
Besides, someone is willing to vouch for you for two years.
What?
She raised her voice unintentionally.
What do you mean someone?
Who is it?
Well, I wasn't supposed to tell you at all.
It just slipped out.
I swore not to say a word about it.
Turns out there are a few people who care about you and for whom this house was a warm home for years.
In my opinion, he's doing it mainly for Lucy.

So that as she really is looking down from above as you feel, she'll be at ease knowing her daughter has a roof over her head, a warm and gentle smile spread on his lits, and mainly that someone is watering her garden.
He felt relieved that this conversation was behind him, as if some burden had been lifted from his shoulders, from his heart.
He knew there was no need for this house now, that all parties would benefit from the situation.

And most importantly, that this house remained pink, cared for and lovingly tended, instead of gathering dust until he would decide to sell it at a good price that would leave him with a worthy profit, just as he had planned from the start.
He had been restless for almost a month, trying to find a creative solution for the situation with the girl, without damaging himself and without burdening her.

something that would serve him too, but that she could handle, and if she couldn't succeed, she could always return the house to him, all this time they stood motionless at the entrance of the house, standing opposite each other like two actors in a scene.
Only now, once the words were said, did they both feel the need to sit down.
She opened the door.
They entered inside, he collapsed into the armchair, and she into the chair beside it.
She looked at him and softly said, I think we should drink something to celebrate this.
What would you like?"
He smiled.
I'll have a beer.
Then I will too.
And she was already behind the bar, pulling two cold gold star beers from the fridge and pouring them into glasses in her usual way, tilting the glass to prevent foam from forming.
They stood side by side at the wooden bar and clinked their glasses.
To your health and the long life of this house," he smiled.
And to your health too, she replied.
In her heart, she thought that her pink house had a life of its own.
It refused to die.
It found its own way to survive.
She sipped slowly from the cold beer, savoring its bitterness that came at such a sweet moment.
Thank you, Yehuda.
She broke the silence between them.
I really don't know why you're doing this, but I truly thank you."
Well, no need to exaggerate.
He cleared his throat with embarrassment.
It's just for now, remember?
I'm not doing anything with it anyway.
Suddenly, he stood up abruptly.
I have to go.
Don't forget to set up a meeting with Claude, and if you need anything, you know where to find me.
He extended his hand to shake hers with a formality that seemed to mask his embarrassment and excitement.
As he walked to the door, he found her suddenly beside him and simply embracing him.
He gave a surprised and awkward smile and left.
